,{"text":"Okay.","index":456,"end_time":1599.59,"speaker_id":1,"start_time":1599.07,"speaker_name":"Rob Schnitzler"},{"text":"So you can check that out.","index":457,"end_time":1600.91,"speaker_id":1,"start_time":1599.59,"speaker_name":"Rob Schnitzler"},{"text":"All right, Sounds great.","index":458,"end_time":1602.39,"speaker_id":1,"start_time":1600.91,"speaker_name":"Rob Schnitzler"},{"text":"Thank you all cool.","index":459,"end_time":1603.39,"speaker_id":0,"start_time":1602.39,"speaker_name":"Tristan Pelligrino"},{"text":"Thanks, Rob.","index":460,"end_time":1604.11,"speaker_id":0,"start_time":1603.39,"speaker_name":"Tristan Pelligrino"},{"text":"Bye.","index":461,"end_time":1604.83,"speaker_id":1,"start_time":1604.35,"speaker_name":"Rob Schnitzler"}],"dateString":"2026-01-21T15:00:00.000Z","host_email":"tristan.pelligrino@marketersindemand.com","meeting_link":"https://us02web.zoom.us/j/84801960534?pwd=tq9BFJBUCprJPJ0W7NRoAlJYH7bZXD.1&jst=2","participants":["tristan.pelligrino@marketersindemand.com,rob@rugged-robotics.com,baylee.gunnell@marketersindemand.com,nathalie.mintjens@marketersindemand.com","rob@rugged-robotics.com","baylee.gunnell@marketersindemand.com","nathalie.mintjens@marketersindemand.com"],"transcript_url":"https://app.fireflies.ai/view/01KFBFVS2VPDS1VEDPH92R5G0M","organizer_email":"tristan.pelligrino@marketersindemand.com"}'::jsonb,
    '{"label":"neutral","confidence":0.82,"bullets":["Reviewed staging environment updates; Demir and Natalie to finalize design edits together.","Confirmed ABM outreach velocity at 500 emails/week; open rate noted but no replies yet.","Rob to provide blacklist CSV to avoid ABM outreach to sensitive contacts.","Explored RB2B tool for visitor-level data; Rob to evaluate privacy implications.","Planned LinkedIn ad retargeting for contacts unresponsive to initial campaign flows."],"highlights":[{"quote":"Nothing we''ve ever gotten from paid has been an actual lead that we like.","speaker":"Rob Schnitzler"},{"quote":"We can have a blacklist in Clay to prevent specific contacts from ABM flows.","speaker":"Tristan Pelligrino"},{"quote":"Let me think about it... it''s a little bit of like who do you want to be.","speaker":"Rob Schnitzler"}],"topics":["abm","ads","targeting","website","delivery","risk"],"model":"openai/gpt-4-0613","version":1,"generated_at":"2026-01-23T00:00:00Z"}'::jsonb,
    '{"fireflies_summary":{"notes":"## **Website Development and Design**\n\nThe team made key progress on the staging environment and case study page updates to support upcoming marketing efforts.\n\n- **Design updates for the case study page were delivered today**, with text alignment adjusted to be left-aligned for better readability (02:00)  \n    - Natalie confirmed the updated design was sent and ready to share with Rob quickly  \n    - Demir is handling major design and development changes on the staging environment to improve template structure  \n    - This work supports the overall goal of improving user experience and content presentation to boost engagement  \n    - The timeline aligns with the scheduled delivery of suggested case study edits tomorrow to finalize content  \n\n- **Structural questions on the staging environment will be addressed in a separate session** between Rob, Demir, and Natalie to refine the backend templates (01:10)  \n    - This ensures technical feasibility and smooth integration before the next deployment phase  \n    - Coordination between design and development teams aims to reduce rework and speed rollout  \n    - The staging environment improvements will enable more flexible content management and faster iterations  \n\n## **Account-Based Marketing (ABM) Email Campaigns**\n\nThe ABM email outreach volume increased significantly, but open rates are high with no replies yet, prompting refinement plans.\n\n- **Over 500 emails were sent last week, averaging about 100 per business day, with good open rates but zero replies so far** (02:35)  \n    - Rob noted the copy is low on calls to action, which may explain the lack of replies  \n    - He proposed tracking multiple opens to identify engaged contacts for targeted manual follow-up  \n    - Tristan agreed to generate reports from Smartly showing contacts with multiple opens to support this effort  \n    - Avoiding excessive API calls to HubSpot by limiting event pushes keeps the system stable while retaining analytics in source systems  \n\n- **Rob emphasized the importance of layering manual outreach on top of automated emails for better conversion** (04:03)  \n    - He shared that direct outreach often yields better quality leads than paid or automated channels  \n    - The current email copy is more exploratory than pushy, matching their cautious market approach  \n    - The team will reassess after completing a full email sequence cycle to decide on expanding or refining targets  \n    - The ABM strategy targets a small, specific market slice where personal relationships and handholding matter  \n\n## **Paid Media and Lead Quality Assessment**\n\nPaid channels provide awareness but generate mostly low-quality leads, impacting follow-up prioritization and analytics.\n\n- **Google search and LinkedIn ads generate leads that rarely qualify as sales-ready opportunities** (06:40)  \n    - Rob explained leads often come from individuals with limited buying power or outside core targets  \n    - Paid leads are tracked in HubSpot but often categorized as outbound due to data gaps on mid-funnel activity  \n    - The sales team prioritizes direct and enterprise contacts, reducing focus on paid channel leads  \n    - Rob stressed the need to map lead sources back to deal records for more accurate attribution and strategy refinement  \n\n- **Tristan proposed analyzing deal records to backtrack lead origins and optimize channel spend** (08:40)  \n    - Rob agreed deal records are the best proxy for qualified opportunities despite some gaps  \n    - They will test pulling data from Factors and Smartly to validate lead engagement against actual pipeline  \n    - This will help identify which paid and automated channels contribute to revenue, informing future investments  \n    - The approach aims to balance awareness generation with efficient resource allocation  \n\n## **Target Account List Expansion and Segmentation**\n\nThe team plans to test a wider target list after completing initial email sequences to reach more potential clients.\n\n- **Rob shared a list of over 200 companies labeled as Automated Facilities (AF) for potential expansion beyond core accounts** (17:52)  \n    - This list includes data center general contractors, manufacturing systems integrators, and warehouse players  \n    - The current direct outreach targets trades, which convert faster but cover a narrower segment  \n    - Expanding to AF accounts allows passive education campaigns to reach less-touched prospects  \n    - The idea is to clean and refine the list before launching campaigns, using tools like Clay for segmentation  \n\n- **Rob emphasized the difference in sales approach between trades and enterprise accounts** (15:27)  \n    - Trades yield faster, transactional deals while enterprise sales require longer handholding and partnership building  \n    - The team will run a full sequence on existing targets before deciding on wider campaigns  \n    - The AF list provides a scalable way to increase market coverage without overloading sales reps  \n    - This strategy supports long-term growth by nurturing a broader funnel at lower cost  \n\n## **Do Not Contact List and Contact-Level Opt-Outs**\n\nA system to exclude priority contacts from automated outreach will be implemented to respect relationships and reduce friction.\n\n- **Rob requested a way to exclude individual contacts from ABM email flows to avoid redundant or sensitive outreach** (19:55)  \n    - Tristan proposed building a blacklist in Clay that blocks these contacts before sending to Smart Lead  \n    - Rob agreed to coordinate with sales to provide the list via HubSpot exports or CSVs for easy updates  \n    - Natalie suggested uploading do-not-contact lists retroactively to prevent sending to these contacts in current campaigns  \n    - This measure balances automation efficiency with personalized relationship management to reduce risk  \n\n- **The team recognized the list size will likely remain small, making manual updates feasible** (22:28)  \n    - Regular syncing between sales and marketing will keep the blacklist current and accurate  \n    - This process prevents alienating important contacts while maintaining campaign scale  \n    - It reflects a careful approach to automation that respects existing trust and communication channels  \n\n## **LinkedIn Ad Campaign Planning and Retargeting**\n\nLinkedIn audience size is currently small, so the team will delay campaign launch to allow list growth and retargeting potential.\n\n- **Current LinkedIn contact audience is around 300, below the preferred minimum of 500 for efficient targeting** (24:30)  \n    - Tristan suggested expanding the list with additional roles to reach the threshold  \n    - Rob preferred waiting two weeks to let the email flows engage contacts before activating ads  \n    - The ads would then serve as retargeting to re-engage less responsive prospects  \n    - This phased approach aims to maximize ad spend ROI and avoid premature campaigns  \n\n- **Rob will review existing creative assets to determine if new ad formats are needed** (25:28)  \n    - The team agreed to postpone execution until the audience size and engagement justify the spend  \n    - This cautious approach aligns with their strategy to prioritize quality over quantity in lead generation  \n    - It also allows better integration of paid and organic outreach for sustained impact","outline":null,"keywords":["ABM","email campaigns","Factors analytics","lead qualification","blacklist management","LinkedIn ads"],"overview":"- **Website Updates Progress:** Case study page design delivered; key changes improve user experience and engagement for marketing efforts.  \n- **ABM Campaign Insights:** Over 500 emails sent, strong open rates but no replies; copy needs better calls to action for improved engagement.  \n- **Lead Quality Challenges:** Paid leads mostly low-quality; focus shifts to higher-value direct and enterprise contacts for better sales alignment.  \n- **Target Account Expansion:** New list of 200 Automated Facilities companies to broaden outreach; prepares for passive education campaigns to wider prospects.  \n- **Exclude Priority Contacts:** A \"do not contact\" list will be created to respect relationships and reduce outreach friction during automation.  \n- **LinkedIn Campaign Delay:** Current audience too small for ads; team will wait for list growth and improved engagement before launching campaigns.","action_items":"\n**Rob Schnitzler**\nExport blacklist contact list from CRM and coordinate with sales team on do-not-contact individuals (22:30)\nDiscuss adoption of RB2B personal identification tool internally with Derek and assess approach (26:00)\n\n**Nathalie Mintjens**\nUpdate and send suggested edits to case studies by tomorrow (01:50)\nUpload updated case study page design with left-aligned text to Rob promptly (02:00)\nUpload do-not-contact lists retroactively to Smart Lead to prevent outreach errors (23:30)\n\n**Tristan Pelligrino**\nCoordinate with Rob and Natalie to generate reports of multiple email opens from Smartly for manual outreach consideration (05:30)\nWork with team on building blacklist functionality in Clay for exclusion before sending contacts to Smart Lead (21:45)\nPrepare to test wider account list (''AF accounts'') in Clay for potential expanded ABM campaigns after initial sequence completion (18:00)\nFollow up on LinkedIn retargeting campaign readiness after audience size increases and more contact engagement data available (25:30)\n"},"migrated_from":"contract_meetings","original_id":"5e6ef439-797d-4412-8f1f-3c03e446bcb9","master_marketer":{"status":"migrated"}}'::jsonb,
